This is a tricky one, but there is indeed an *O*(*n*) solution: it&#39;s possible to make a single pass through the array, with appropriate bookkeeping, to count all such subarrays.

---

To start with, let&#39;s pretend that we only want to count subarrays that *start* with their maximum value. We could do that by keeping a stack containing all values that we&#39;ve encountered that haven&#39;t yet been exceeded by later values. For example, if so far we&#39;ve processed [10, 5, 8, 4, 2, 4, 3, 1], then the stack would contain [10, 8, 4, 4, 3, 1]: the 5 was exceeded by the 8, and the 2 was exceeded by the second 4, but all the other values are still in the stack. If the next value in the array is another 8, then we update the stack (to [10, 8, 8]), and the size of the stack (3) is the number of subarrays that *end* with the new 8 and *start* with their maximum value. (Do you see why?) So we have something like this:

```
public int countSubarraysThatStartAtMax(final int[] array) {
    final List&lt;Integer&gt; stack = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();
    int result = 0;
    for (final int element : array) {
        // update stack:
        while (stack.size() &gt; 0 &amp;&amp; stack.get(stack.size() - 1) &lt; element) {
            stack.remove(stack.size() - 1);
        }
        stack.add(element);
        // use updated stack:
        result += stack.size();
    }
    return result;
}
```

(Note: You may notice that this involves two nested loops, where the outer loop has *n* iterations and each occurrence of the inner loop has potentially up to *n* iterations; so you might think that the total cost is in *&amp;Theta;*(*n*&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt;) time. However, the *total* number of iterations of the inner loop, across *all* occurrences, adds up to at most *n*, because each iteration removes an element from the stack, and we only add a total of *n* elements to the stack. So the total cost is in *O*(*n*) time. The same logic applies to all of the below as well.)

---

Next, let&#39;s pretend that we only want to count subarrays that *end* with their maximum value. Of course, we could do this the same way as the above, but going right-to-left instead of left-to-right; but let&#39;s imagine that we specifically need to do this with a left-to-right pass. (We&#39;ll ultimately need to combine this with the above, into a single more-complicated pass, so they need to go in the same direction.) For this, we keep a stack containing all values *and corresponding indices* that we&#39;ve encountered that haven&#39;t yet been exceeded *or matched* by later values. For example, if so far we&#39;ve processed [10, 5, 8, 4, 2, 4, 3, 1], then the stack would contain [(10, 0), (8, 2), (4, 5), (3, 6), (1, 7)]: this time we&#39;ve included the indices, and we&#39;ve discarded the first occurrence of 4 because there was a later one. If the next value in the array (at index&amp;nbsp;=&amp;nbsp;8) is another 4, then we pare the stack down to just [(10, 0), (8, 2)], and the number of subarrays that end at that 4 and have max&amp;nbsp;=&amp;nbsp;4 is 8&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;2. (Do you see why?) Then we add that 4 to the stack. So we have something like this:

```
private static final class StackElement {
    public final int value;
    public final int index;

    public StackElement(final int value, final int index) {
        this.value = value;
        this.index = index;
    }
}

public int countSubarraysThatEndAtMax(final int[] array) {
    final List&lt;StackElement&gt; stack = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();
    int result = 0;
    for (int index = 0; index &lt; array.length; ++index) {
        final int element = array[index];
        // remove obsolete elements from stack:
        while (stack.size() &gt; 0
               &amp;&amp; stack.get(stack.size() - 1).value &lt;= element
        ) {
            stack.remove(stack.size() - 1);
        }
        // use updated stack:
        final int indexOfLastGreaterElement =
            stack.size() == 0
                ? -1
                : stack.get(stack.size() - 1).index;
        result += index - indexOfLastGreaterElement;
        // add new element to stack:
        stack.add(new StackElement(element, index));
    }
    return result;
}
```

---

Now, we need to combine the above, while not double-counting subarrays that both start and end with their maximum value. The not&amp;ndash;double-counting might seem simple; at first glance, it seems that that we can change `countSubarraysThatStartAtMax` from considering &quot;values that we&#39;ve encountered that haven&#39;t yet been exceeded by later values&quot; to only considering &quot;values that we&#39;ve encountered that haven&#39;t yet been exceeded *or matched* by later values&quot;, so that it only counts arrays that start with their maximum value *and don&#39;t end with that value*. The problem, though, is that if we remove old values from the stack as soon as they&#39;re matched by a later value, then we won&#39;t count a subarray like [4, 2, 4, 3]: we&#39;ll remove the first 4 as soon as we see the second 4 even though there may be more subarrays that continue past the second 4. And we might think that we can remove the first 4 and then immediately re-add it, but in a case like [4, 2, 4, 2, 4, 2, 4, 2, 4], we&#39;d have to remove and re-add multiple 4s at once, such that the algorithm as a whole would require worst-case *&amp;Theta;*(*n*&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt;) time.

The solution to this is to change `countSubarraysThatStartAtMax` so that instead of using the literal size of the stack, it stores a `stackSize` field on stack elements, so that it doesn&#39;t need to store multiple copies of the same element:

```
private static final class StackElement {
    public final int value;
    public final int stackSize;

    public StackElement(final int value, final int stackSize) {
        this.value = value;
        this.stackSize = stackSize;
    }
}

public int countSubarraysThatStartButDontEndAtMax(final int[] array) {
    final List&lt;StackElement&gt; stack = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();
    int result = 0;
    for (final int element : array) {
        // remove obsolete elements from stack:
        StackElement popped = null;
        while (stack.size() &gt; 0
               &amp;&amp; stack.get(stack.size() - 1).value &lt;= element
        ) {
            popped = stack.remove(stack.size() - 1);
        }
        // use updated stack:
        final int stackSize =
            stack.size() == 0
                ? 0
                : stack.get(stack.size() - 1).stackSize;
        result += stackSize;
        // add new element to stack:
        if (popped == null || popped.value &lt; element) {
            stack.add(new StackElement(element, stackSize + 1));
        } else {
            stack.add(new StackElement(element, popped.stackSize + 1));
        }
    }
    return result;
}
```

And now it&#39;s reasonably straightforward to combine them:

```
private static final class StackElement {
    public final int value;
    public final int lastIndex;
    public final int stackSize;

    public StackElement(
        final int value,
        final int lastIndex,
        final int stackSize
    ) {
        this.value = value;
        this.lastIndex = lastIndex;
        this.stackSize = stackSize;
    }
}

public int countSubarraysThatStartOrEndAtMax(final int[] array) {
    final List&lt;StackElement&gt; stack = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();
    int result = 0;
    for (int index = 0; index &lt; array.length; ++index) {
        final int element = array[index];
        // remove obsolete elements from stack:
        StackElement popped = null;
        while (stack.size() &gt; 0
               &amp;&amp; stack.get(stack.size() - 1).value &lt;= element
        ) {
            popped = stack.remove(stack.size() - 1);
        }
        // use updated stack:
        final int stackSize =
            stack.size() == 0
                ? 0
                : stack.get(stack.size() - 1).stackSize;
        result += stackSize;
        final int indexOfLastGreaterElement =
            stack.size() == 0
                ? -1
                : stack.get(stack.size() - 1).lastIndex;
        result += index - indexOfLastGreaterElement;
        // add new element to stack:
        if (popped == null || popped.value &lt; element) {
            stack.add(new StackElement(element, index, stackSize + 1));
        } else {
            stack.add(new StackElement(element, index, popped.stackSize + 1));
        }
    }
    return result;
}
```

The idea is to find left greater and right greater element for each element A[i] and then traverse from i to len(A) and count number of subarrays that can be formed by including leftGreaterIndex(i)...i and i...rightGreaterIndex(i). The leftGreaterIndex and rightGreaterIndex can be found using monotonic stack. So the count of such subarrays can be calculated as res += (r - i + 1) + (i - l + 1) - 1; // -1 in the end because subarray at l...r will be counted twice.

Time complexity : O(n), where n = len(A)
Space complexity : O(n)

Here is my implementation:

    public static long count(List&lt;Integer&gt; A) {
        int n = A.size();
        int[] left = leftGreater(A);
        int[] right = rightGreater(A);
        long res = 0;
        for (int i = 0; i &lt; n; i++) {
            int l = left[i];
            int r = right[i];
            res += (r - i + 1) + (i - l + 1) - 1; // -1 because subarray at l...r will be counted twice
        }
        return res;
    }

    private static int[] leftGreater(List&lt;Integer&gt; A) {
        int n = A.size();
        int[] res = new int[n];
        Stack&lt;Integer&gt; st = new Stack&lt;&gt;();
        for (int i = 0; i &lt; n; i++) {
            while (!st.isEmpty() &amp;&amp; A.get(st.peek()) &lt;= A.get(i)) {
                st.pop();
            }
            res[i] = st.isEmpty() ? i : st.peek();
            st.push(i);
        }
        return res;
    }

    private static int[] rightGreater(List&lt;Integer&gt; A) {
        int n = A.size();
        int[] res = new int[n];
        Stack&lt;Integer&gt; st = new Stack&lt;&gt;();
        for (int i = n - 1; i &gt;= 0; i--) {
            while (!st.isEmpty() &amp;&amp; A.get(st.peek()) &lt;= A.get(i)) {
                st.pop();
            }
            res[i] = st.isEmpty() ? i : st.peek();
            st.push(i);
        }
        return res;
    }

