You can not get separate repeated capture group values in Java repeating the capture group itself. That will only capture the value of the last iteration.

What you might do is make use of the `\G` anchor, and get capture group 1, capture group 2, and then all the letters a, b, c, d etc... in capture group 3.

    (?:https://(\S*?)/v(\S*?)/|\G(?!^))([^/\s]+)/?

The pattern matches:

- `(?:` Non capture group for the alternatives
  - `https://` Match literally
  - `(\S*?)` Capture **group 1**, match optional non whitespace chars
  - `/v` Match literally
  - `(\S*?)` Capture **group 2**, match optional non whitespace chars
  - `/` Match literally
  - `|` Or
  - `\G(?!^)` Assert the current position at the end of the previous match, not at the start
- `)` Close the non capture group
- `([^/\s]+)` Capture **group 3**, match 1+ characters other than `/` or a whitespace char
- `/?` Match an optional `/`


[Regex demo](https://regex101.com/r/GmHRKP/1) | [Java demo](https://ideone.com/DIl7hF)

Example

	String regex = &quot;(?:https:\\/\\/(\\S*?)\\/v(\\S*?)\\/|\\G(?!^))([^/\\s])(?:/|$)&quot;;
    String string = &quot;https://123/v1/a/b/&quot;;
    
    Pattern pattern = Pattern.compile(regex);
    Matcher matcher = pattern.matcher(string);
    
    while (matcher.find()) {
        for (int i = 1; i &lt;= matcher.groupCount(); i++) {
        	String grp = matcher.group(i);
        	if (grp != null) {
        		System.out.println(&quot;Group &quot; + i + &quot;: &quot; + grp);	
        	}
        }
    }

Output

    Group 1: 123
    Group 2: 1
    Group 3: a
    Group 3: b

&lt;hr&gt;

Or a bit more precise match:

    (?:https://(\d+)/v[a-z]*(\d+)/|\G(?!^))([a-z]+)/?

[Regex demo](https://regex101.com/r/hqGuyt/1)

You could use [`java.net.URI`](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/6/docs/api/java/net/URI.html) which has getters for various URI-components.

```java
