answers.body_markdown:
**PROBLEM**

The problem with this recursion is that it runs infinitely (never stops) and this causes a **stack overflow error**.

The reason why the error is at line **19**:

```java
return (Calcul(a, L + 1, a / L + 1));
```

is because it&#39;s the line that makes the recursive call. (calls `Calcul`)

**WHY IS THE RECURSION RUNNING INFINITELY**

This is because the only condition that terminates the recursion never gets fulfilled.

```java
if (L * W == a )
```

so more calls to `return (Calcul(a, L + 1, a / L + 1));` just continue getting made.

**SOLUTION**

I am not sure if the required values of **L and W** don&#39;t need to contain decimals, but I shall use integers like you did.

What we need is to find the multiples of the area with the least difference. For example, when area is `20`. L and W will be `5x4` respectively.

```java
import java.util.Arrays;

public class Main {
	public static void main(String[] args) {
		System.out.println(Arrays.toString(getLandW(20)));
	}

	public static int[] getLandW(int area) {
		int LandW[] = new int[2], difference = Integer.MAX_VALUE;

		for (int factor = area, otherFactor, diff; factor &gt; 0; factor--)

            // Stop when we find a factor
			if ((area % factor) == 0) {
				otherFactor = area / factor;
				diff = Math.abs(factor - otherFactor);

                // When the difference of the factors
                // is less than current
				if (diff &lt; difference) {
					difference = diff;
					LandW[0] = factor;
					LandW[1] = otherFactor;
				}
			}

		return LandW;
	}
}
```

